--- a/devcontainer/commands/vsss.md
+++ b/devcontainer/commands/vsss.md
@@ -89,6 +89,8 @@ session_file=.vss/sessions/<start-ISO>.md
 
 **Launcher side (already implemented in `/workspace/vibe`).** When claude exits while the marker says `active=1` and `remaining>=1`, the launcher counts down to `resume_at` (+2 min pad; 30 min fallback if the field is unusable; Ctrl-C cancels), decrements `remaining`, and relaunches `claude --continue "/vsss --resume"` — which lands in this spec's Resumption protocol above. The relaunch cost is one window from the X budget, whatever the halt cause was — the launcher cannot reliably distinguish credit exhaustion from a crash, and both are legitimate resume cases; a user-typed `/exit` mid-run also triggers the countdown, which is why the countdown is loud and cancellable.
 
+**Launcher-side stall watchdog (the reason the marker refresh above is now load-bearing).** Interactive claude does NOT exit when a Pro/Max usage window runs out — it blocks forever at an interactive usage-limit picker, so the relaunch above never fires on its own. The launcher now backgrounds claude, watches a container-side heartbeat file (`.vss/heartbeat`, refreshed by `settings.local.json` hooks on tool activity while a marker exists), and kills a genuinely wedged claude itself. The kill only arms when THREE conditions hold: the marker is `active=1`; the marker was refreshed DURING the current launcher session (proven via the marker's mtime against a session-start reference file) — this is exactly why your per-iteration marker refresh (above) matters: without it, a live `--sessions` run could look like a stale crash-left marker and never get the stall protection; and the heartbeat has gone stale past the threshold. Defaults: `VIBE_STALL_SECS=1800` (heartbeat staleness before a kill is even considered — 30 min, chosen because hooks fire for subagent tool calls too, so long Task/Agent dispatches keep the heartbeat fresh, and a single Bash call is capped at 10 min by Claude Code itself), `VIBE_STALL_POLL_SECS=60` (watchdog poll interval), `VIBE_STALL_GRACE_SECS=120` (warn-then-wait before killing), `VIBE_STALL_KILL_PAUSE_SECS=10` (pause between the in-container kill attempt and the host-side fallback). All four are env-overridable per launch. On kill: with `remaining>=1` the launcher drops straight into the countdown/relaunch above; on the final window (`remaining=0`) the loop is simply not entered and vibe exits cleanly instead of hanging forever. The skill needs NO new behaviour beyond the marker refresh it already specifies above — this is entirely a launcher-side addition.
+
 **Budget arithmetic under `--sessions`.** Overriding the resume-budget rule above for this mode only: each auto-resumed window gets a FRESH `BUDGET_HOURS` allowance (the whole point is spanning multiple 5h windows); `remaining` is what bounds total run length. `--hours` still caps each window individually.
 
 ## Loop structure
diff --git a/vibe b/vibe
index 49728f6..aa81a9c 100755
--- a/vibe
+++ b/vibe
@@ -484,6 +484,42 @@ fable_billing_phase() {
 # relaunches `claude --continue "/vsss --resume"`. The skill sets active=0 at
 # any clean Final-state exit, so finished loops never relaunch. Manual
 # override: delete .vss/auto-resume, or Ctrl-C during the countdown.
+#
+# Stall watchdog (heartbeat-driven kill of a wedged usage-limit picker):
+# interactive claude does NOT exit when a Pro/Max usage window runs out — it
+# blocks forever at an interactive picker, so the relaunch loop above never
+# runs on its own. settings.local.json's PreToolUse/PostToolUse/Stop hooks
+# (see the heredoc below) write an epoch to .vss/heartbeat while the marker
+# exists; launch_claude_supervised backgrounds claude, captures its PID, and
+# runs vibe_stall_watchdog alongside it. The watchdog's kill gate is THREE
+# conditions, ALL required, so a crash-left marker in an unrelated later
+# interactive session is never mistaken for a live --sessions run: (1) marker
+# active=1 (auto_resume_field, not auto_resume_pending, so the FINAL window —
+# remaining=0 — is still protected from an unwanted kill); (2) the marker was
+# refreshed DURING THIS launcher session — proven portably via
+# `[ marker -nt ref ]` against a session-start reference file (VIBE_SESSION_REF)
+# — OR the call site is a relaunch, which arms unconditionally via the literal
+# sentinel "-" (a freshly relaunched window may be stalled at the picker
+# before the skill gets a chance to refresh anything); an EMPTY ref (e.g.
+# mktemp failure) NEVER arms — fail-safe toward not killing; (3) the
+# heartbeat is provably stale (auto_resume_stalled, default 1800s — 30 min of
+# no hook events, including subagent tool calls, reliably means the picker,
+# not a legitimately long-running command). On trigger: warn, wait a grace
+# period, re-check all three, then kill in-container first
+# (vibe_container_kill_claude), pause for that to land, and fall back to the
+# host client PID. With relaunches remaining this drops straight into the
+# existing countdown/relaunch loop below; on the final window (remaining=0)
+# the loop is simply not entered and the launcher exits cleanly instead of
+# hanging forever. The watchdog's own lifetime is bounded by claude-PID
+# liveness alone (kill -0 in its poll loop) — no EXIT-trap dependency, so the
+# pre-existing clipboard-watcher EXIT trap is untouched; an orphaned watchdog
+# (launcher died mid-wait) notices claude's death within one poll interval.
+# Ctrl-C during the countdown deactivates the marker (auto_resume_deactivate)
+# via a per-iteration INT trap — cancel means cancel, but crash-left markers
+# must still resume, so nothing else touches the marker on any other exit
+# path. Claude's exit status is captured past the old `set -e`-guarding
+# `|| true` swallow and propagated as vibe's own final exit code
+# ($CLAUDE_EXIT).
 
 # auto_resume_field <file> <key> — echoes the last value for key, digits only
 # (missing file, missing key, or non-numeric value → echoes nothing). Keeping
@@ -516,6 +552,117 @@ auto_resume_decrement() {
     "$file" > "$tmp" && mv "$tmp" "$file"
 }
 
+# auto_resume_deactivate <file> — rewrite the marker with active=0, preserving
+# every other line. Same awk-to-temp+mv pattern as auto_resume_decrement.
+# Idempotent (running it twice leaves active=0). Missing file → return 0
+# WITHOUT creating one (cancelling a run that never wrote a marker is a
+# no-op, not an error).
+auto_resume_deactivate() {
+  local file="$1" tmp
+  [ -f "$file" ] || return 0
+  tmp="${file}.tmp.$$"
+  awk -F= 'BEGIN{OFS="="} $1=="active" {$2="0"} {print}' \
+    "$file" > "$tmp" && mv "$tmp" "$file"
+}
+
+# auto_resume_heartbeat_write <file> — atomically writes the current epoch
+# (date +%s) as the file's only content; same temp+mv pattern. Guarded so it
+# can NEVER return non-zero or trip `set -e` — an unwritable .vss dir (or any
+# other failure) is a silent no-op, and the temp file is cleaned up rather
+# than left behind if the write or rename fails partway.
+auto_resume_heartbeat_write() {
+  local file="$1" tmp
+  tmp="${file}.tmp.$$"
+  if ! { date +%s > "$tmp" 2>/dev/null && mv "$tmp" "$file" 2>/dev/null; }; then
+    rm -f "$tmp" 2>/dev/null || true
+  fi
+  return 0
+}
+
+# auto_resume_stalled <hb_file> <now_epoch> <stall_secs> — 0 (stalled) iff
+# the file's first line is a digits-only epoch AND now-epoch > stall_secs
+# (strict). Fail-safe returns 1 (not stalled) for a missing/empty file,
+# non-numeric content, a future epoch, and the exact boundary (gap ==
+# stall_secs) — a malformed or absent heartbeat must never look stale enough
+# to justify a kill.
+auto_resume_stalled() {
+  local file="$1" now="$2" thresh="$3" epoch gap
+  [ -f "$file" ] || return 1
+  epoch=$(head -1 "$file" 2>/dev/null)
+  case "$epoch" in
+    ''|*[!0-9]*) return 1 ;;
+  esac
+  gap=$(( now - epoch ))
+  [ "$gap" -gt "$thresh" ]
